name: Give notice and get consent for a planned activity on a SSSI

components.content:
You should use this form to give notice of a planned activity on a site of special scientific interest (SSSI) that needs Natural England’s consent. 

Your planned activities must be taking place within a SSSI.

Only certain individuals can submit a notice. They must be either: 
* the land owner
* the land occupier
* someone with the land owner or occupier's permission 

You can only apply for permission for one land owner or occupier at a time. You can apply for permission for activities across more than one SSSI if the land owner or occupier is the same.

You may be asked for proof of permission to submit notice if you are not the owner.
 
## Check if the activity is an ORNEC

You need to give notice for SSSI consent if your planned activities match at least one of the operations requiring Natural England’s consent for the relevant SSSI site. These are known as operations requiring Natural England's consent (ORNEC).

You can check if an activity is an ORNEC for any given SSSI by using the free [designated sites system](https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/) website.

Search for the relevant SSSI, select 'View details'  then 'View ORNECs'.

## Processing time

The processing time for this form is approximately 4 months. Natural England will contact you by email at this time.

If you have already applied for another Natural England licence or have applied for planning permission, you do not need to submit a notice separately via this form.

You can, if you wish, upload supporting documents to help Natural England assess how your activities might affect the SSSI. These documents can help the decision-making process, but they are not compulsory. You can upload as many as you think are useful.

* a map of your planned activities
* any other related permission documents
* any scheme document details
* risk assessments, identifying any potential risks linked to your planned activity and how you plan to manage them
* method statements, including any mitigation measures to minimise impacts on the SSSI
* ecological surveys, if relevant to your activities
* any other existing or live consent notices
